Dr. Ray Peat mentioned one of the reasons he dislikes language "biologically speaking" is that there is actually a slight visuospatial intelligence drop in babies once they start speaking in and using language. I wonder if being raised bilingual would worsen or alleviate this.

My guess is being taught to speak in two languages from the get-go would make you "believe" in words less and thus you may resist from falling into the trap of literally taking them too literally. You can "peer" behind the languages. Bilingualism is closer to the Adamic language.

I would guess hypothyroidism and poor metabolism leads to learned helplessness partly because one of the symptoms of them is having cold hands. You forget you can take action, do things yourself, fight, craft, labour, etc. unless you can actually feel your hands in every moment.

Dr. Peat had an interesting quote on how each of your bodyparts participates in every situation, e.g. your toes and liver are a part of the experience of you falling in love even if you do not think of them in that context. A good circulation to the hands makes them more evident.

In a similar way, chronically cold feet can produce systematic stress signals that cause anemia, bad digestion, etc. even if no one thinks of them as potentially participating in those processes unless made aware of it. So I guess we should keep us having our hands in our mind.

If you square this with Dr. Walter Alvarez claiming all flus, upper respiratory tract viruses, colds, etc. are first detectable in the intestine and only afterwards appear in the throat etc. it makes sense because the acidic vigour of the digestive procession would destroy them.

Dr. Ray Peat mentioned often times in autumn and winter people get a cold or flu after they skip a meal that they usually always have at the same one time. E.g. every day at 2 in the afternoon you eat lunch, but one day you skip it due to work. Digestion gets used to periodicity.

So if you're on the road, driving, or in an office, flying, etc. and don't have access to your regular food source, just making a stop for a cup of coffee and some gas station food like those beef jerkies and pastries might not be the worst idea of all time.
